Abstract

The following notes and scripts are based on the following sources: Introductory Econometrics - A Modern Approach by Jeffrey M. Wooldridge is the main text for the statistical content. This text will be referenced as (Wooldridge).

The companion text Using R for Introductory Econometrics by Florian Heiss provides specific R scripts in support of the main text and the inspiration for my scripts, notes and graphics. I will reference this document as (Heiss). The following is from Part 1 - Regression Analysis with Cross-Sectional Data, Chapter 2 of (Heiss).

2 The Simple Regression Model

2.1 Simple OLS Regression

We want to estimate the population parameters \(\hat{\beta_{0}}\) and \(\hat{\beta_{1}}\) of the simple regression model:
\(y = \hat{\beta_{0}} + \hat{\beta_{1}}x + \mu\)[2.1]
According to (Wooldridge, Section 2.2, Equations 2.17, 2.19, page 26) we can estimate the OLS regression line with:
\(\hat{\beta_{0}} = \bar{y} - \hat{\beta_{1}}\bar{x}\)[2.2]
\(\hat{\beta_{1}} = \frac{Cov(x,y)}{Var(x)}\)[2.3]
Task: From the wooldridge::ceosal1 data set involving CEO Salary (salary) and Return on Equity (roe) calculate the statistics for estimating the population parameters \(\hat{\beta_{0}}\) and \(\hat{\beta_{1}}\) for the roe variable to estimate salary.
  1. Review the roe and salary variables from the data set:
data(ceosal1, package = "wooldridge")
str(ceosal1)

##  $ lsales  : num  10.23 9.21 8.72 9.7 9.99 ...
##  - attr(*, "time.stamp")= chr "25 Jun 2011 23:03"
  1. From (Wooldridge, Equation 2.19 page 26) use the pedestrian approach to estimate \(\hat{\beta}_1\) where we need the Cov(roe,salary) and the Var(roe):
cov_roe_salary <- stats::cov(ceosal1$roe, ceosal1$salary)
var_roe <- stats::var(ceosal1$roe)
b1_hat <- cov_roe_salary/var_roe

\(Cov(salary,roe)\) = 1342.538398

\(Var(roe)\) = 72.5649898

\(\hat{\beta}_1 = \frac{Cov(salary,roe)}{Var(roe)}\) = 18.5011863

  1. From (Wooldridge, Equation 2.17 page 26) estimate \(\hat{\beta}_0\) where we need the means for roe and salary and \(\hat{\beta}_1\):
b0_hat <- mean(ceosal1$salary) - b1_hat * mean(ceosal1$roe)

\(\hat{\beta}_0 = \bar{y} - \hat{\beta_{1}}\bar{x} =\) 963.1913365

2.2 Coeffcients, Fitted Values, and Residuals

(Wooldridge, Section 2-3b, page 32) presents three properties of OLS statistics. The three properties (Heiss, page 76)are:

  1. Sum and sample mean of the residuals: \(\sum_{i=1}^n \hat{\mu_{i}} = 0 \Rightarrow \bar{\hat{\mu}}_{i} = 0\)[2.7]

  2. Sample covariance between the regressors and the OLS residuals: \(\sum_{i=1}^n x_{i}\hat{\mu}_{i} = 0\) \(\Rightarrow\) \(Cov(x_{i}, \hat{\mu}_{i}) = 0\)[2.8]

  3. The mean is always on the line: \(\bar{y} = \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 \cdot \bar{x}\)[2.9]

Task: Take the above wage and education data set and confirm the three properties of OLS.
  1. Property 1 – Mean of the residuals \(\hat{\mu_{i}}\) = 0:
mu_hat <- stats::resid(wage_educ_lm)
mu_hat_mean <- mean(mu_hat)

Mean of \(\hat{\mu_{i}}\) = -1.1949804^{-16}

  1. Property 2 – The sample covariance between the regressors and the OLS residuals is zero. \(Cov(x_{i},\hat{\mu}_{i}) = 0\)
cov_x_mu <- stats::cov(wage1$educ, mu_hat)

Cov of \(Cov(x_{i},\hat{\mu}_{i})\) = 4.0650626^{-15}

  1. Property 3 – The point \((\bar{x},\bar{y})\) is always on the OLS regression line. \(\bar{y} = \hat{\beta_{0}} + \hat{\beta_{1}} * \bar{x}\)
y_mean <- mean(wage1$wage)

The \(\bar{y}\) = 5.8961027

lm_coef <- coef(wage_educ_lm)
y_mean_lm <- lm_coef[1] + lm_coef[2] * mean(wage1$educ)

\(\hat{\beta_{0}} + \hat{\beta_{1}} * \bar{x}\) = 5.8961027

2.3 Goodness of fit

Task: Using the above data of salary on roe compute the \(R^2\) or coefficient of determination three different ways where (Wooldridge, Equations 2.33,2.34,2.35 page 34) defines:.

Total sum of the squares (SST) = \(\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i} - \bar{y})^2 = (n - 1) \cdot Var(y)\)[2.10]

Explained sum of the squares (SSE) = \(\sum_{i=1}^n(\hat{y}_{i} - \bar{y})^2 = (n - 1) \cdot Var(\hat{y})\)[2.11]

Residual sum of the squares (SSR) = \(\sum_{i=1}^n(\hat{\mu}_{i} - 0)^2 = (n - 1) \cdot Var(\hat{\mu})\)[2.12]


(Wooldridge, Equation 2.38, page 35) defines \[R^2 = \frac{SSE}{SST} = 1 - \frac{SSR}{SST}\] or \[R^2 = \frac{Var(\hat{y})}{Var(y)} = 1 - \frac{Var(\hat{\mu})}{Var(y)}\]

  1. Compute the SST, SSE, SSR:
n <- length(ceosal1$salary)
SST <- (n - 1) * stats::var(ceosal1$salary)
SSE <- (n - 1) * stats::var(fitted(roe_salary_lm))
SSR <- (n - 1) * stats::var(resid(roe_salary_lm))

\(SST = (n - 1) \cdot Var(y)\) = 3.9173298^{8}

\(SSE = (n - 1) \cdot Var(\hat{y})\) = 5.166419^{6}

\(SSR = (n - 1) \cdot Var(\hat{\mu})\) = 3.8656656^{8}

  1. Compute \(R^2\) via \(Var(\hat{y})/Var(y)\):
R_2_1 <- SSE/SST

\(Var(\hat{y})/Var(y)\) = 0.0131886

  1. Compute \(R^2\) via \(1 - Var(\hat{\mu})/Var(y)\)
R_2_2 <- 1 - (SSR/SST)

\(1 - Var(\hat{\mu})/Var(y)\) = 0.0131886

  1. Compute \(R^2\) using stats::cor() function:
R_2_3 <- stats::cor(ceosal1$salary, fitted(roe_salary_lm))^2

stats::cor() = 0.0131886

The stats::summary() function can also show us the \(R^2\) value as “Multiple R-squared”:

stats::summary.lm(roe_salary_lm)
##

## F-statistic: 2.767 on 1 and 207 DF,  p-value: 0.09777

2.4 Nonlinearities

According to (Wooldridge, page 37) “…it is rather easy to incorporate many non-linearities into simple regression analysis by appropriately defining the dependent and independent variables” (i.e. a variable transformation).

In taking the above example of wage regressed on education suppose we believe that each year of education increases wage by a constant percentage. The percentage of wage change for one unit of education is the same at any starting value for years of education. A model that gives a constant percentage effect is:

\(log(wage) = \beta_{0} - \beta_{1}educ + \mu\)[2.10]
Task: Using equation [2.10] estimate the linear model of log(wage) (i.e. the natural log of wage) regressed on educ. 
log_wage_educ_lm <- stats::lm(log(wage) ~ educ, data = wage1)
b0 <- coef(log_wage_educ_lm)[[1]]
b1 <- coef(log_wage_educ_lm)[[2]]

The regression of log(wage) on education is: \[\widehat{log(wage)} = 0.584 + 0.083 \cdot educ\] The model’s estimate for \(\hat{\beta}_{1}\) is 0.083 or multiplying by 100 we can say that \(\widehat{log(wage)}\) increases by 8.3% for every additional year of education.

Task: Exponentiate equation [2.10] and plot the nonlinear nature of how wage increases for every additional year of education.
  1. By exponentiating [2.10], we can write an equation involving just wage and educ: \[\widehat{wage} = exp(\hat{\beta_{0}} + \hat{\beta_{1}}educ + \hat{\mu)}\]
educ <- seq(0, 19, 1)
log_wage <- b0 + b1 * educ
wage <- exp(log_wage)
wage_exp_dt <- data.table(
  educ = educ,
  wage = wage
)
head(wage_exp_dt)
##    educ     wage
## 1:    0 1.792789
## 2:    1 1.947443
## 3:    2 2.115437
## 4:    3 2.297923
## 5:    4 2.496151
## 6:    5 2.711480
  1. Plot wage vs educ:
RplotterPkg::create_scatter_plot(
  df = wage_exp_dt,
  aes_x = "educ",
  aes_y = "wage",
  title = "Wage Regressed on Education",
  subtitle = "wage = exp(0.59 + 0.083*educ)",
  connect = TRUE,
  x_limits = c(0,19),
  x_major_breaks = seq(0,19,1),
  y_limits = c(1,9),
  y_major_breaks = seq(1,9,1)
)

\(\hat{\beta}_{1} =\) 63.5379552

roe_salary_constant_lm <- stats::lm(formula = salary ~ 1, data = ceosal1)

\(\hat{\beta}_{0} =\) 1281.1196172

2.6 Expected Values, Variances, and Standard Errors

(Wooldridge, Section 2-5b, page 45) presents Theorem 2.2 on the sampling variances of the OLS estimators \(\hat{\beta}_{0}\) and \(\hat{\beta}_{1}\). (Heiss, page 82) gives the following equivalent formulas:

\(se(\hat{\beta}_{0}) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{n-1}}\cdot\frac{\hat{\sigma}}{sd(x)}\cdot\sqrt{\bar{x^2}}\)[2.15]
\(se(\hat{\beta}_{1}) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{n-1}}\cdot\frac{\hat{\sigma}}{sd(x)}\)[2.16]

where \(\hat{\sigma}^2 = \frac{n-1}{n-2}\cdot Var(\hat{\mu}_{i})\) is the variance of the error term \(\mu\). \(\hat{\sigma}\) = \(\sqrt{\hat{\sigma}^2}\) is known as the standard error of the regression (SER) or residual standard error

Task: Using the data set Wooldridge::meap93, compute the standard errors of the OLS estimators using the above equations.

Note that from the data set we are regressing math performance scores of schools on the share of students eligible for a federally funded lunch program.

  1. Review the lnchprg and math10 variables from the data set:
data("meap93", package = "wooldridge")

  1. Estimate the OLS model:
math_lunch_lm <- stats::lm(formula = math10 ~ lnchprg, data = meap93)
  1. Compute the residual standard error (SER):
n = stats::nobs(math_lunch_lm)
SER <- sd(resid(math_lunch_lm)) * sqrt((n-1)/(n-2))

The SER = 9.5659385

  1. Compute the standard errors for \(\hat{\beta}_{0}\) and \(\hat{\beta}_{1}\):
beta_0_se <- (SER/sd(meap93$lnchprg))/sqrt(n-1) * sqrt(mean(meap93$lnchprg^2))
beta_1_se <- (SER/sd(meap93$lnchprg))/sqrt(n-1)

\(se(\hat{\beta}_{0}) =\) 0.9975824 \(se(\hat{\beta}_{1}) =\) 0.0348393

2.7 Monto Carlo Simulations

2.7.1 One sample

Task: We are given population coefficients for \(\beta_{0}\) = 1, \(\beta_{1}\) = 0.5, and set the sd of the error term \(\mu\) to \(\sigma\) = 2. If we draw a random sample (\(n\) = 1000) of the independent variable \(x\), then the population \(y\) values can be computed from the population coefficients. If we estimate the coefficients via OLS, using \(x\) and \(y\) as input, how does the estimated \(\hat{y}\) compare with the population \(y\) values.
  1. Set the seed, set the population parameters, and draw a random sample of \(x\) with mean = 4 and sd = 1:
set.seed(1234567)
n <-  1000
b_0 <- 1
b_1 <- 0.5
x <- stats::rnorm(n, 4, 1)
  1. Draw a random sample of the error term \(\mu\) which has a mean of 0 and sd of 2:
mu <- stats::rnorm(n, 0, 2)
  1. Compute the population \(y\) values:
y <- b_0 + b_1 * x + mu
  1. Estimate the coefficients via OLS:
model_lm <- stats::lm(y ~ x)

The estimated coefficients via OLS are: 1.2091716, 0.4384287

  1. Plot both the population \(y\) and the \(\hat{y}\) estimated from OLS:
dt <- data.table(
  x = x,
  y = y,
  fit = model_lm$fitted.values
)

RplotterPkg::create_scatter_plot(
  df = dt,
  aes_x = "x",
  aes_y = "y",
  title = "Simulated sample and OLS Regression Line",
  rot_y_tic_label = TRUE
) + geom_line(aes(y = fit), color = "blue", linetype = "twodash")

Task: Compute the standard errors of the above \(\hat{\beta_{0}}\) and \(\hat{\beta_{1}}\) OLS estimates.

(Wooldridge, Theorem 2.2, page 47) states that the standard errors involve the mean values of \(x^2\) (\(\bar{x^2}\)) and sum of the squares \(\sum^n_{i=1}(x-\bar{x})^2\) where: \[Var(\beta_{0}) = \frac{\sigma^2 \bar{x^2}}{\sum^n_{i=1}(x-\bar{x})^2}\] \[Var(\beta_{1}) = \frac{\sigma^2}{\sum^n_{i=1}(x-\bar{x})^2}\]

  1. Compute mean(\(x^2\))
x_2_mean <- mean(x^2)

The mean of \(x^2\) = 16.9664407

  1. Compute \(\sum^n_{i=1}(x-\bar{x})^2\)
x_sum_2 <- sum((x - mean(x))^2)

\(\sum^n_{i=1}(x-\bar{x})^2\) = 990.4103944

Standard error of \(\hat{\beta_{0}}\) = 0.2617687

Standard error of \(\hat{\beta_{1}}\) = 0.063551

2.7.2 Many samples

Task: Repeat the simulation in the above section by computing a random set of \(x\) values along with 10000 random normal sets of the error term \(\mu\)
  1. Set the seed, set the population parameters, and draw a random sample of \(x\) with mean = 4 and sd = 1:
set.seed(1234567)
n <-  1000
simulations_n <- 10000
b_0 <- 1
b_1 <- 0.5
sd_mu <- 2
x <- stats::rnorm(n, 4, 1)
# initialize vectors for storing OLS coefficient estimates
b_0_ols <- numeric(simulations_n)
b_1_ols <- numeric(simulations_n)
  1. Repeat the simulation 10000 times and store the estimated OLS coefficients:
for(j in 1:10000){
  # draw a sample of y
  mu <- stats::rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = sd_mu)
  y <- b_0 + b_1 * x + mu
  
  # estimate coefficients by OLS and store them in the vectors
  b_ols <- stats::coefficients(lm(y~x))
  b_0_ols[j] <- b_ols["(Intercept)"]
  b_1_ols[j] <- b_ols["x"]
}
  1. Compute the means of the 10000 estimated OLS coefficients noting that \(\beta_{0}\) = 1 and \(\beta_{1}\) = 0.5: E(\(\hat{\beta}_{0}\)) = 0.9985388

E(\(\hat{\beta}_{1}\)) = 0.5000466

sampled_se(\(\beta_{0}\)) = 0.262837

b_0_se = (1/sqrt(n-1))*(2/sd(x))*sqrt(mean(x^2))
b_1_se = (1/sqrt(n-1))*(2/sd(x))

2.7.3 Violation of SLR.4

(Wooldridge, section 2-5, page 40) presents set of assumptions for simple linear regression (SLR). He outlines 5 assumptions (SLR.1 - SLR.5). (Heiss, page 82) list these assumptions and considers the violation of SLR.4 \(E(\mu_{i}|x_{i}) = 0\) (zero conditional mean).

Task: Repeat the many sample Monte Carlo simulation in the above section 2.7.2 and compute a randomly selected population \(\mu\) where the \(\mu\)’s mean is conditional on \(x\). For example set \(E(\mu_{i}|x_{i}) = \frac{x_{i}-4}{5}\)
  1. Set the seed, set the population parameters, and draw a random sample of \(x\) with mean = 4 and sd = 1:
set.seed(1234567)
n <-  1000
simulations_n <- 10000
b_0 <- 1
b_1 <- 0.5
sd_mu <- 2
x <- stats::rnorm(n, mean = 4, sd = 1)
# initialize vectors for storing OLS coefficient estimates
b_0_ols <- numeric(simulations_n)
b_1_ols <- numeric(simulations_n)
  1. For \(\mu\) set the vector of means \(\frac{(x_{i}-4)}{5}\) and sd = sd_mu and repeat the simulation 10000 times and store the estimated OLS coefficients:
for(j in 1:10000){
  # draw a sample of y
  mu <- stats::rnorm(n, mean = (x-4)/5, sd = sd_mu)
  y <- b_0 + b_1 * x + mu
  
  # estimate coefficients by OLS and store them in the vectors
  b_ols <- stats::coefficients(lm(y~x))
  b_0_ols[j] <- b_ols["(Intercept)"]
  b_1_ols[j] <- b_ols["x"]
}
  1. Compute the means of the 10000 sampled estimated OLS coefficients noting that \(\beta_{0}\) = 1 and \(\beta_{1}\) = 0.5:

E(\(\hat{\beta}_{0}\)) = 0.1985388

E(\(\hat{\beta}_{1}\)) = 0.7000466

  1. Compute the standard error of the sampled estimated OLS coefficients:
sample_b_0_se = sqrt(var(b_0_ols))

sample_b_1_se = sqrt(var(b_1_ols))

sampled_se(\(\hat{\beta}_{0}\)) = 0.262837

sampled_se(\(\hat{\beta}_{1}\)) = 0.0637892

2.7.4 Violation of SLR.5

SLR.5 addresses homoscedasticity of \(\mu\) where \(Var(\mu_{i}|x{i}) = \sigma^2\).
Task: As an example of the SLR.5 violation, repeat the many sample Monte Carlo simulation in the above section 2.7.2 and set \(Var(\mu_{i}|x_{i}) = \frac{4}{e^{4.5}}\cdot e^{x_{i}}\)
  1. Set the seed, set the population parameters, and draw a random sample of \(x\) with mean = 4 and sd = 1:
set.seed(1234567)
n <-  1000
simulations_n <- 10000
b_0 <- 1
b_1 <- 0.5
x <- stats::rnorm(n, mean = 4, sd = 1)
# initialize vectors for storing OLS coefficient estimates
b_0_ols <- numeric(simulations_n)
b_1_ols <- numeric(simulations_n)
mu_var <- numeric(simulations_n)
  1. For \(\mu\) set the vector of means to 0 and \(sd(\mu_{i})\) = \(sqrt(\frac{4}{e^{4.5}}\cdot e^{x_{i}})\) and repeat the simulation 10000 times and store the estimated OLS coefficients:
for(j in 1:10000){
  # draw a sample of y
  mu <- stats::rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = sqrt(4/exp(4.5) * exp(x)))
  mu_var[j] <- var(mu)
  y <- b_0 + b_1 * x + mu
  
  # estimate coefficients by OLS and store them in the vectors
  b_ols <- stats::coefficients(lm(y~x))
  b_0_ols[j] <- b_ols["(Intercept)"]
  b_1_ols[j] <- b_ols["x"]
}
  1. Compute the means of the 10000 estimated OLS coefficients noting that \(\beta_{0}\) = 1 and \(\beta_{1}\) = 0.5:

E(\(\hat{\beta}_{0}\)) = 1.0019001

E(\(\hat{\beta}_{1}\)) = 0.4992376

  1. Compute the standard error of the sampled estimated OLS coefficients:
sample_b_0_se = sqrt(var(b_0_ols))

sample_b_1_se = sqrt(var(b_1_ols))

sampled_se(\(\hat{\beta}_{0}\)) = 0.2994501

sampled_se(\(\hat{\beta}_{1}\)) = 0.0852313

  1. compare the sample coefficient standard errors to (Heiss, equations 2.15, 2.16, page 82)
b_0_se = (1/sqrt(n-1))*(2/sd(x))*sqrt(mean(x^2))
b_1_se = (1/sqrt(n-1))*(2/sd(x))

se(\(\beta_{0}\)) = 0.2617687

se(\(\beta_{1}\)) = 0.063551

According to (Heiss, page 90) the variances and thus the standard errors provided by the equations are incorrect.
